Reports switch expressions and statements where every branch has a common subexpression, and the 'switch' can be moved inside. This action shortens the code. In many cases, it's reasonable to extract the resulting switch expression to a separate variable or method. Example: 'switch (value) {
    case 0 -> System.out.println("zero");
    case 1 -> System.out.println("one");
    case 2, 3, 4 -> System.out.println("few");
    default -> System.out.println("many");
  }' After the quick-fix is applied: 'System.out.println(switch (value) {
    case 0 -> "zero";
    case 1 -> "one";
    case 2, 3, 4 -> "few";
    default -> "many";
  });' This inspection is applicable only for enhanced switches with arrow syntax. This inspection depends on the Java feature ''switch' expressions', which is available since Java 14. New in 2022.3

